Q1 again now.  Using this to read out group/guild/raid/tell chat messages that I get using Alerts.<br>
<br>
However... there is one problem.<br>
<br>
Here's a sample group chat message<br>
[Sat Sep 27 12:02:30 2005] Soandso tells the group, 'I am going to start pulling now if we are ready'<br>
<br>
I use an alert with the following trigger...<br>
%0 tells the group, '%1'<br>
... and an associated alert string...<br>
%0 tells the group, %1<br>
<br>
This all works great presuming nobody uses any contractions...<br>
It reads aloud &quot;Soandso tells the group, I am going to start pulling now if we are ready&quot;<br>
<br>
If instead the chat message was:<br>
[Sat Sep 27 12:02:30 2005] Soandso tells the group, 'I'm going to start pulling now if we are ready'<br>
<br>
What it then reads out is:<br>
&quot;Soandso tells the group, I&quot;<br>
<br>
It cuts off everything after the first apostropy.  Thats because in my trigger I have the '%1' in single quotes.  <br>
<br>
The answer would seem simple... don't put the single quotes there, but that doesn't work.  It would seem that the alert REQUIRES that there be a non wildcarded character at the end for it to look for.  <br>
<br>
For example If I run the first message...<br>
[Sat Sep 27 12:02:30 2005] Soandso tells the group, 'I am going to start pulling now if we are ready'<br>
...with an alert string of...<br>
%0 tells the group, %1<br>
...then what it reads is...<br>
&quot;Soandso tells the group, &quot;<br>
Without anything in the %1 variable because there was nothing for it to look for AFTER that variable so it returns empty.<br>
<br>
There's several ways to fix this:<br>
- Add an EndOfLine symbol that can be added so that I can tell it to read the whole remainder the line into the final wild card<br>
- Just make it so when an alert string ends with a wild card it gets the remainder of the line instead of blank.<br>
- Or Hmmm I wonder what would happen if I stuck a /0x0D or a /0x0A in at the end (one is carriage return, the other is linefeed, cant remember which is which)<br>
<br>
Thinking about it further, its probably just a bug that when you have the wild card at the end it comes back empty.  It should get the remainder of the line in that case I'd think.<br>
<br>
Unfortunatly EQ1's logs are more &quot;human readable&quot; than EQ2s are with all the extra /\/\ type characters bracketing the text.<br>
